<section class="card">
  <h2>What to Do in Each Gardening Season</h2>

  <p>
    Gardening is a hobby with a changing rhythm.
  </p>

  <p>
    The work is not the same in winter,
    spring,
    summer,
    and fall.
  </p>

  <p>
    That seasonal variety is part of what makes the hobby interesting.
  </p>

  <h3>Winter: Plan and Start Slowly</h3>

  <p>
    Winter is a good time to check frost dates,
    choose a small first project,
    sort seeds,
    sketch a simple garden layout,
    and start slow-growing crops indoors if your season requires it.
  </p>

  <p>
    If you want to start seeds indoors,
    use the <a href="/tools/seed-start-planner/">seed start planner</a>
    to count backward from your transplant window.
  </p>

  <p>
    This is also a good time to decide what kind of gardener you want to be this year:
    a container gardener,
    a seed starter,
    a herb grower,
    a raised bed beginner,
    or someone testing one new crop.
  </p>

  <h3>Spring: Plant in Stages</h3>

  <p>
    Spring is exciting,
    but it is also when beginners often rush.
  </p>

  <p>
    Cool-season crops can usually start earlier than warm-season crops.
    Lettuce,
    peas,
    radishes,
    kale,
    onions,
    spinach,
    and many brassicas are not the same as tomatoes,
    peppers,
    cucumbers,
    squash,
    beans,
    and basil.
  </p>

  <p>
    A good spring habit is to plant in stages,
    watch the forecast,
    and avoid treating the average last frost date as a guaranteed safe date.
  </p>

  <h3>Summer: Maintain and Observe</h3>

  <p>
    Summer gardening is mostly about steady care.
  </p>

  <p>
    Water consistently,
    harvest often,
    support tall plants,
    remove crops that are finished,
    and notice what handles your space well.
  </p>

  <p>
    This is when you learn whether your containers dry out quickly,
    whether your tomato needs stronger support,
    and whether your lettuce prefers spring more than summer.
  </p>

  <h3>Fall: Learn From the Season</h3>

  <p>
    Fall is when the garden starts giving you answers.
  </p>

  <p>
    Which crops finished before frost?
    Which ones needed more time?
    Which plants were worth the space?
    Which ones sounded good but did not fit your season?
  </p>

  <p>
    In many climates,
    fall can also include garlic planting,
    late greens,
    frost protection,
    row cover,
    seed saving,
    composting,
    and cleanup.
  </p>

  <p class="muted">
    A garden teaches you something different in every season.
  </p>
</section>

